@node ABOUT "PROJECT/About KingFisher"
@prev MENU-PROJECT
@nex
KingFisher Release 2.0
Copyright © 1992-1995 Udo Schuermann
All rights reserved.

For @{b}Distribution Rights@{ub}, click @{" here " link DISTRIB}

For my @{b}translators@{ub}, click @{" here " link TRANSLATORS}

For @{b}registration, upgrades, and support@{ub} click @{" here " link SUPPOORT}

The KingFisher Logo is available in up to 16 grey shades if you are running Kickstart 3 or later on a display providing 8 or more colors.
@endnode

@node STATUS "PROJECT/Status"
Presents you with some information about your connection to the server, including an estimate of what percentage of the @{" server's " link KFSERVER} total time your client has used (this is always 100% unless more than one client have connected to the server.)

With the SHIFT key or MMB (Middle Mouse Button) held down, you get a very detailed listing (dumped to a console window, from where you can cut & paste it) which is the same as when you invoke KFServer with the STATUS parameter when it is already running. The purpose is to give you information about the databases and client connections in the @{" server " link KFSERVER}. This sort of information is useful mainly for diagnostic purposes but might be fun to examine if you're curious.
	If you have KingCON installed you can resize the console window and scroll through the contents forward and backwards!
@endnode

@node OPENDATABASE "PROJECT/Open Database"
Select a different database from among those that the server knows about. This function is rarely useful if you have only a single database installed.

The @{" server " link KFSERVER} knows only about databases that have a .kfdb file in the server's directory.

You can cancel the selection by closing the window or by pressing the RMB (Right Mouse Button.)
@endnode

@node INSTALLDATABASE "PROJECT/Install Database"
Copies a .kfdb file from one disk to the server's directory so that the server can find it (immediately.)

The first file requester selects the .kfdb file to install. The second file requester saves the file, possibly under a new name, to the server's directory. The database is immediately available with the @{" PROJECT/Open Database " link OPENDATABASE} command.

There are some points of which you should be aware:

  *	@{lindent 8}All that the server needs to access a database is a properly configured .kfdb file. Such a file occupies a trivial amount of diskspace.@{lindent 0}

  *	@{lindent 8}Certain settings in a .kfdb file specify the location of files (record and index files); if these settings do not specify a path, KingFisher will add the path to the directory where the .kfdb file was copied from. This makes the database immediately available!@{lindent 0}

  *	@{lindent 8}When installing a CD-ROM database, you may wish to manually copy the index files from the CD-ROM to a writable volume and adjust the .kfdb file to reflect this. KingFisher will then permit you to alter the @{" flags " link GAD_FLAGS}, reindex, and rebuild the @{b}Version Links@{ub} of the database (although you will not be able to add records to the database unless those files are also copied to a writable volume.)
@endnode

@node DEFINEDATABASE "PROJECT/Define Database"
NOTE:	This command is not yet available. Click @{" here " link NEWDB} for the necessary steps.
@endnode

@node PRINT "PROJECT/Print"
Send one or more fish (records) to the printer. If you print from KingFisher's main window, only the currently displayed fish is printed. If you print from the "Caught Fish" window, then all fish in the @{" Search Set " link SEARCHSET} are printed.

Output is configurable with the options in the @{" PREFERENCES/Printing " link PREFSPRINT} menu. In particular, output may--if you so desire--use a different layout than the display window.

@{b}NOTE:@{ub}@{lindent 16}	The printer device will remain open until you explicitly close it with the @{" PROJECT/Release printer " link PRINTRELEASE} command. This prevents other tasks from mixing their output with that of KingFisher.@{lindent 0}

@{b}NOTE:@{ub}@{lindent 16}	Only database records can be printed at this time, not the clipboard contents or the contents of a .Product-Info file.@{lindent 0}
@endnode

@node PRINTRELEASE "PROJECT/Release printer"
If this option is not ghosted, then it closes the printer device after you have printed all you wish to print. This permits other tasks to use the printer again.

The current page in use will be ejected by this command.
@endnode

@node EXPORT "PROJECT/Export"
Save one or more fish (records) to a file. If you export from KingFisher's main window, only the currently displayed fish is saved. If you export from the "Caught Fish" window, then all fish in the @{" Search Set " link SEARCHSET} are saved.

Output is configurable with the options in the @{" PREFERENCES/Exporting " link PREFSEXPORT} menu. In particular, output may--if you so desire--use a different layout than the display window.

@{b}NOTE:@{ub}@{lindent 16}	The export file will remain open until you explicitly close it with the @{" PROJECT/Close export file " link PRINTRELEASE} command. This prevents other tasks from using (and possibly blocking) the file before you are truly finished with your export selections.@{lindent 0}

@{b}NOTE:@{ub}@{lindent 16}	Only database records can be exported at this time, not the clipboard contents or the contents of a .Product-Info file.@{lindent 0}
@endnode

@node EXPORTCLOSE "PROJECT/Close export file"
If this options is not ghosted, it closes the export file after you have saved to it all you wish to save. This permits other tasks to access the file.
@endnode

@node QUIT "PROJECT/Quit"
@next MENU-PROJECT
The @{" PREFERENCES/Global/Confirm quit " link PREFSCONFIRMQUIT} menu item lets you to specify whether or not you wish KingFisher to ask if you really want to quit.

  *	@{lindent 8}If you find yourself frequently quitting KingFisher without meaning to, you should turn that option on.@{lindent 0}

  *	@{lindent 8}If the "Really quit KingFisher" requester goes on your nerves, turn the option off.@{lindent 0}

If the @{" Auto-save on exit " link PREFSAUTOSAVE} option is enabled, then KingFisher will save all your current settings so that they can be restored when next you start the program.
@endnode

@node APPENDFILE "EDIT/Append fish from file"
@prev MENU-EDIT
The file you specify for imported records may contain one or more records. The file must conform to the @{" Product-Info " link PI} specifications. All valid records from the given file will be appended to the database and @{b}Version Links@{ub} extablished. The index is automatically updated (and saved to disk when the database is closed.)
@endnode

@node APPENDTREE "EDIT/Append fish from tree"
Performs the same operation as @{" EDIT/Append fish from file " link APPENDFILE} on every file in a given directory tree that is named #?.pi, .Product-Info, or @{" Product-Info " link PI}. A status window keeps you informed of progress. You can interrupt the scan by closing the status window; you must confirm such an action before the scan is actually aborted.

The index is automatically updated (and saved to disk when the database is closed.)
@endnode

@node DELETEFISH "EDIT/Delete fish"
Truncates the database by deleting the current fish (record) and all that follow. You must confirm the action before it will be actually performed. The records are actually removed from the database files and are not recoverable unless you make prior arrangements to copy them elsewhere.
@endnode

@node COPYTOCLIP "EDIT/Copy to clipboard"
Copies the current record to the clipboard from where it can be reimported via the @{" EDIT/Append fish from file " link APPENDFILE} command. The next 'Copy to clipboard' operation will @{b}overwrite@{ub} the previous clipboard contents. @{b}To save multiple@{ub} fish (records) to the clipboard, use the 'Copy to clipboard' command in the "Caught Fish" window.

The record is stored in clipboard unit 0 as an IFF FTXT.
@endnode

@node APPENDFROMCLIIP "EDIT/Append from clipboard"
The contents of all IFF FTXT records found in the clipboard's unit 0 are processed and--if valid records--appended to the current database.
@endnode

@node REINDEX "EDIT/Reconstruct database index"
This command asks the server to throw away all indexing information on the current database, then scan the database file(s) in an effort to reconstruct the information necessary to access individual records.

Both the main index, and the QuickIndex are rebuilt by this command, wherefore both must be writable.

@{b}WARNING:@{ub}@{lindent 16}	The main index stores the @{b}Version Links@{ub} as well as the @{" flags " link GAD_FLAGS}. If you reindex a database you will lose both of these sets of information!@{lindent 0}

After reconstructing the database index you should use the @{" Build Version links " link REBUILDLINKS} command to rebuild the @{b}Version Links@{ub}, as well.

A database can be reindexed only if you are the only client using it.
@endnode

@node REBUILDLINKS "EDIT/Build Version Links"
Reconstructs the @{b}Version Links@{ub} for the current database. The main database index must be writable.

The following options are available before the operation begins:

	[x] Clear existing links
		@{lindent 16}Removes all previous @{b}Version Links@{ub} before the operation begins. This step assures that no confusion ensues when two or more programs reference a single ancestor or successor through the use of multiple 'Build Version Links' commands that were issued with different options.@{lindent 0}

	[x] Eliminate (Roman) numeric additions˛
		@{lindent 16}Programs such as "bBaseII" and "bBaseIII" or "DiskSalv" and "DiskSalv 2" are considered the same. Use of this option does not adversely affect processing.@{lindent 0}

	[x] Double-check by authorsą ł
		@{lindent 16}Two programs with the same name are considered for linking only if their respective author sets intersect. In other words, "MonkeyCommand" by Marcus Antonius, and "MonkeyCommand" by Ricky Rocket are considered distinctly different, but if the second is written by Ricky Rocket @{b}and@{ub} Marcus Antonius (and perhaps others), then the programs @{b}are@{ub} linked.@{lindent 0}

	[x] Sort links by versionł
		@{lindent 16}As CD-ROM databases may not necessarily list software in version order, this option will examine the 'version' fields and order the links so that earlier versions (even if stored later in the database) are at the start of the version list.
	This option depends heavily on correct version numbers in the database (i.e. the .version field must be formatted according to the Commodore Style Guide, as reflected in the @{" Product-Info " link PI} specification.)
	This option is not available with a older Release 1 databases such as the "1000 Fish Disks" database that ships with KingFisher (the option will be disabled in that case.)@{lindent 0}

@{b}Version Links@{ub} can be build only if you are the only client using this database. The database must be writable.

NOTE: In versions earlier than 2.10, KingFisher relied on an O(n˛) algorithm to perform this operation. A vastly superior algorithm was then designed, which rebuilds the links in linear, O(n) time!
__________
ą@{lindent 8}	This option will be implemented in a future release.@{lindent 0}

˛@{lindent 8}	Use of this option will slow down processing only if no QuickIndex is available.@{lindent 0}

ł@{lindent 8}	Use of this option will slow down processing!@{lindent 0}
@endnode

@node EDITFORMAT "EDIT/Edit custom format file"
This permits you to create or edit a custom display, print, or export format for KingFisher.

KingFisher will suspend its operation until you are finished with the editor program that it invokes.

If the environment variable EDITOR is not set (i.e. 'ENV:EDITOR' does not exist) then KingFisher will use 'c:ED' instead to edit the .format file, otherwise it will use your favorite editor!

@{b}NOTE:@{ub}	@{lindent 8}If you are running KingFisher on a custom screen instead of the default public screen, then the editor may appear on the Workbench or default public screen; look for it there. This is because KingFisher's custom screens are not made into a (default) public screen that your editor would recognized and use.@{lindent 0}

@{b}NOTE:@{ub}	@{lindent 8}If you edit the display format file currently in use by KingFisher, you must manually reload this file. A future release of KingFisher will use file notification to assure that any alteration to the file (even when not modified with KingFisher's knowledge) will automagically update the display.@{lindent 0}
@endnode

@node EDITEXPRESSION "EDIT/Edit search expression"
Edit the current search expression. You may also press the RETURN or the 'x' key to activate the @{" Search Expression " link GAD_EXPRESSION} gadget.
@endnode

@node EDITMASKS "EDIT/Edit Masks"
When @{" selected for use " link PREFSSEARCHUSEMASK} the @{b}Search Mask@{ub} operates during a search to select only specific records for searching, usually eliminating the vast majority of records.

Alter the @{b}Search Mask@{ub} usable during searches to locate specially flagged fish (records) in the database. The current record's @{" flags " link GAD_FLAGS} are available in the upper right corner. The @{b}Search Mask@{ub} is compared against this combination of flags during a search, allowing you to explicitly exclude certain records, depending on what @{b}flags@{ub} a record has set.

The @{b}Search Mask@{ub} is used only if you have selected the @{" Use Search Masks " link PREFSSEARCHUSEMASK} option.

There are two components to the @{b}Search Mask@{ub}:


@{b}Avoid Mask@{ub}@{lindent 16}
The 'Avoid Mask' is used to @{b}completely eliminate@{ub} any record from the search that has set one of the flags in the 'Avoid Mask.' By default this includes all records with the Deleted (D), Owned (O), and Hidden (H) @{" flags " link GAD_FLAGS}.@{lindent 0}

@{b}Match Mask@{ub}@{lindent 16}
A record not already eliminated by the 'Avoid Mask' is then considered a match only if it has set one of the flags in the 'Match Mask.' By default this includes all records with the Mark (M) @{" flag " link GAD_FLAGS}.@{lindent 0}

@{b}NOTE:@{ub}	@{lindent 8}Fish (records) @{b}without any flags@{ub} set cannot be located with a Search Mask in use!!@{lindent 0}
@endnode

@node SELECTEXPRESSION "SEARCH/Select Expression"
@prev MENU-SEARCH
Every search @{" expression " link EXPRESSIONS} you use in a search is placed into the @{b}Expression History@{ub} list. From this list you may retrieve a previously used expression by clicking on it. The list is available in a scrolling listview by either a menu operation or by use of the @{" Expression History " link GAD_HISTORY} gadget.

The @{b}Expression History List@{ub} can store between 5 and 1024 expressions. The @{b}MaxHistory@{ub} setting controls how many you permit to be stored before the oldest expression is dropped to make room for a new one.
@endnode

@node SEARCHBACKWARD "SEARCH/Search reverse"
Begins a search in reverse direction. You may interrupt the search by closing the "Search Status" window.

If you the @{" Search Options " link PREFSSEARCH} are configured so that you are creating a @{" Search Set " link SEARCHSET} then the current fish is included in the search, otherwise it is skipped.

The Search Expression string gadget must contain a valid @{" Search Expression " link EXPRESSIONS}; if it does not, you will receive a diagnostic error message and the search will not be performed.

You may also initiate a reverse search by pressing the ">" key or clicking on the forward @{" Search Button " link GAD_SEARCH}
@endnode

@node SEARCHFORWARD "SEARCH/Search forward"
Begins a search in forward direction. You may interrupt the search by closing the "Search Status" window.

If you the @{" Search Options " link MENU-SEARCH} are configured so that you are creating a @{" Search Set " link SEARCHSET} then the current fish is included in the search, otherwise it is skipped.

The Search Expression string gadget must contain a valid @{" Search Expression " link EXPRESSIONS}; if it does not, you will receive a diagnostic error message and the search will not be performed.

You may also initiate a forward search by pressing the ">" key or clicking on the forward @{" Search Button " link GAD_SEARCH}
@endnode

@node LOADSEARCH "SEARCH/Load search set"
Reload a @{" Search Set " link SEARCHSET} from disk where the result of a previously performed search has been stored.

Any Search Set that you have currently loaded will be cleared and is lost if it has not been saved with the @{" SEARCH/Save search set " link SAVESEARCH} command.

When a @{b}Search Set@{ub} is loaded, KingFisher will activate the database to which the search set applies. KingFisher will also store the relevant @{" Search Expression " link EXPRESSIONS} to the @{" Expression gadget " link GAD_EXPRESSION} to indicate what parameters produced the @{b}Search Set@{ub}.

While loading the @{b}Search Set@{ub}, KingFisher will retrieve some information from the records of the appropriate database. Large @{b}Search Sets@{ub} may not seem to load very quickly for this reason, bue the slight delay requires much less time than performing the search again.
@endnode

@node SAVESEARCH "SEARCH/Save search set"
@next MENU-SEARCH
Saves the current @{" Search Set " link SEARCHSET} to a file on disk so it can be retrieved later. This saves you the time and effort of executing the search and having to wait for the result again. Search Sets require @{i}approximately @{ui}5 bytes per fish (record) on disk, so that 100 matching records will not require more than approximately 500 bytes on disk!

@{b}NOTE:@{ub}	@{lindent 8}You should make sure that you always add the file extension @{b}.search@{ub} to a saved Search Set, otherwise (when you use the @{" SEARCH/Load search set " link LOADSEARCH} command) the file requester may not show you this Search Set until you alter the file requester's @{b}Pattern@{ub} that specifies which files to include and exclude from the total volume of available files.@{lindent 0}
@endnode

@node VIEWDB "VIEW/Database"
@prev MENU-VIEW
View the records in the currently selected database. This option is always the default when KingFisher starts.

KingFisher automatically re-selects this option when either of the @{" VIEW/Product-Info file " link VIEWPI} or the @{" VIEW/Product-Info clipboard " link VIEWCB} is active @{b}and@{ub} you perform an operation that is only available when a database is viewed (such as selecting the next record.) KingFisher then redisplays the current database record and alerts you to this switch by performing a @{i}DisplayBeep() @{ui}operation, effectively flashing the display and/or playing the system default bell tone (see Workbench's Sound Preferences.)
@endnode

@node VIEWPI "VIEW/Product-Info file"
Select a @{" Product-Info " link PI} file to view.

While the Product-Info file is displayed, any operation performed that relates to the current database will flash the display and revert to the @{" VIEW/Database " link VIEWDB} selection.

This viewing mode is meant to proof-read a Product-Info file of your own construction. This saves you the repetitive cycle of having to add it to a database, then removing it, modifying the file, and adding it once again.
@endnode

@node VIEWCB "VIEW/Product-Info clipboard"
@next MENU-VIEW
View the current clipboard contents as a @{" Product-Info " link PI} record.

While the Product-Info file is displayed, any operation performed that relates to the current database will flash the display and revert to the @{" VIEW/Database " link VIEWDB} selection.

This viewing mode is meant to proof-read a Product-Info file of your own construction, which you have copied into the clipboard from an editor. This saves you the repetitive cycle of having to add it to a database, then removing it, modifying the record, and adding it once again.
@endnode

@node PREFSGLOBAL "PREFERENCES/Global"
@prev MENU-PREFERENCES

	@{" Auto-save on exit " link PREFSAUTOSAVE}
	@{" Confirm quit " link PREFSCONFIRMQUIT}

	@{" External command on forced View Exit " link PREFSENDVIEWINGALERTEXTERN}
	@{" Flash/beep screen on forced View Exit " link PREFSENDVIEWINGALERTFLASH}
@endnode

@node PREFSAUTOSAVE "PREFERENCES/GLOBAL/Auto-save on exit"
If this option is enabled when you quit, KingFisher will automatically store all current settings. These settings are restored when you start KingFisher.

The settings are ordinarily stored to a file named @{" KingFisher2.prefs " link TOOLTYPES} in the current directory. The same file is used for storing the settings as was used when KingFisher was started, meaning that if KingFisher is told to load its settings from a different file, then it is that same file that is also updated when you quit. See the SETTINGS @{" tooltype " link TOOLTYPES} for details on how to specify such an alternate settings file.

When restoring settings and not given a specific file to load them from, KingFisher will look for the file @{b}KingFisher2.prefs@{ub} first in the current directory. If not found there, it will look for it in the ENV:KingFisher/ directory, and finally in the directory named by the logical volume S: (usually SYS:s/ )

If you turn off this option @{b}and@{ub} wish this change to become permanent, then you must use the @{" Save Preferences " link PREFSSAVE} command to update the settings file, otherwise the change will not be saved when KingFisher exits!
@endnode

@node PREFSCONFIRMQUIT "PREFERENCES/GLOBAL/Confirm quit"
Do you hate software that always asks if you really want to quit? Do you have a reflexive habit of closing the window (and quitting programs) before you're actually done? KingFisher accomodates you in either case!

If "Confirm Quit" is checked, KingFisher requires affirmation before it will really quit. Likewise, if this menu item is not checked, then KingFisher instantly quits when you click (and release) the close window gadget.
@endnode

@node PREFSENDVIEWINGALERTEXTERN "External command on forced View Exit"
When you are viewing a Product-Info record (see @{"The View Menu" link MENU-VIEW}) rather than a regular database, and you perform an operation that makes sense only in the context of a database operation (such as selecting the next record or invoking a search operation) then KingFisher is said to be forced to leave View Mode.

When that happens, and this option is checked, then an external command is executed through the shell (CLI) as specified by the END-VIEWING-COMMAND option in the @{" KingFisher2.prefs " link TOOLTYPES} file.

Example: @{b}END-VIEWING-COMMAND=say "Oops, we are now back to viewing the database!"@{ub}

See also @{" Flash/beep screen on forced View Exit " link PREFSENDVIEWINGALERTFLASH} for a less complex alert option.

Note: The human speech software used by the SAY command was discontinued by Commodore after Workbench 2.1 (V38) was released. If you have this software on older disks you may want to consider installing DEVS:narrator.device and LIBS:translator.library. Both work perfectly with later releases of the operating system, and the SAY command can be a lot of fun!
@endnode

@node PREFSENDVIEWINGALERTFLASH "Flash/beep screen on forced View Exit"
When you are viewing a Product-Info record (see @{"The View Menu" link MENU-VIEW}) rather than a regular database, and you perform an operation that makes sense only in the context of a database operation (such as selecting the next record or invoking a search operation) then KingFisher is said to be forced to leave View Mode.

When that happens, and this option is checked, then KingFisher will "flash" all screens so that if you are busy working on something else, the "flash" will alert you that something wants your attention. To customize this feature further, use Workbench's Sound Preferences; you may set thi to "flash" all screens and/or play a sound on your speakers.

This option is available in addition to the more flexible @{" External command on forced View Exit " link PREFSENDVIEWINGALERTEXTERN} option which requires a little work on your part to configure.
@endnode

@node PREFSDISPLAY "PREFERENCES/Display"

	@{" Load custom display format " link PREFSDISPLAYLOAD}
	@{" Show all fields in record " link PREFSSHOWALLFIELDS}
	@{" Use default display format " link PREFSDISPLAYRESET}

	@{" Custom screen " link PREFSDISPLAYCUSTOM}
	@{" Default public screen " link PREFSDISPLAYPUBLIC}

	@{" Center main window " link PREFSDISPLAYCENTER}
	@{" Sticky result window " link PREFSDISPLAYSTICKY}
	@{" Show database title " link PREFSDISPLAYDBTITLE}
	@{" Use external gadget images " link PREFSDISPLAYEXTERNALGADIMAGES}
	@{" Frame groups " link PREFSDISPLAYFRAME}
	@{" Smart refresh " link PREFSDISPLAYREFRESH}
@endnode

@node PREFSDISPLAYLOAD "PREFERENCES/DISPLAY/Load custom display format"
Load a @{" Custom Format " link CUSTOMFORMAT} from a file and applies this to the way fish (records) are displayed in the scrolling view (listview). To remove a custom display format and revert to the builtin default, select the @{" Use default display format " link PREFSDISPLAYRESET} command.

KingFisher remembers the display format in use for every database.

To create or edit a custom format, use the @{" Edit custom format file " link EDITFORMAT} command.

To revert to the built-in default format, use the @{" Use default display format " link PREFSDISPLAYRESET} command.

Using AmigaOS Notification, the file displayed is immediately updated if the version on disk is changed. The display is immediately updated to reflect the new file's contents.
@endnode

@node PREFSSHOWALLFIELDS "PREFERENCES/DISPLAY/Show all fields in record"
Creates a @{" Custom Format " link CUSTOMFORMAT} based on every displayed record's own fields and uses that to create the display of information.

If you currently have a custom display format selected, it will be replaced by this command.

To return to the default display format, select the @{" Used default display format " link PREFSDISPLAYRESET} command; to return to a custom display format, select a new custom display format.

Notice that this command will display non-standard fields as well as fields ordinarily suppressed because they are empty.
@endnode

@node PREFSDISPLAYRESET "PREFERENCES/DISPLAY/Use default display format"
This command reverts back to the builtin default display format.

The command is unavailable if the default display format is already in use.
@endnode

@node PREFSDISPLAYFONT "PREFERENCES/DISPLAY/Font"
KingFisher uses the @{b}Screen Font@{ub} defined by your @{b}Font Preferences@{ub}. This may be a fixed pitch or proportionally spaced font.

Likewise, you may select any font for KingFisher's interface, scalable, bitmapped, fixed width or proportional.

Be advised that KingFisher will not fall back to a smaller font if you select an unreasonably large font.
@endnode

@node PREFSDISPLAYCUSTOM "PREFERENCES/DISPLAY/Custom screen"
@next PREFSDISPLAYPUBLIC
If you are running Kickstart V37 (2.04) then please click @{" here " link CUSTOM37} for assistance in getting KingFisher Release 2 to open on a custom screen, as KingFisher requires Kickstart V38 or later to use the ASL Screen Mode requester.

Any screen mode showing up in the screen mode requester is acceptable to KingFisher, although a lowres (ex: 320x200) may be a debatably silly choice unless you have also (and previously!) chosen a suitably tiny font for KingFisher.

Be advised that KingFisher will not fall back to a smaller font if your current selection is not reasonable for the size of the selected screen.
@endnode

@node CUSTOM37 "Getting KingFisher to open on a custom screen under V37"
@font courier.font 13
@next MAIN
@prev MAIN
First of all, quit all copies of KingFisher so that your changes to the @{" KingFisher2.prefs " link TOOLTYPES} file are not accidentally overwritten again when you later quit the program.

You need to edit the KingFisher2.prefs file and locate the "Screen" item, which should be one of the very first ones listed. The following example uses an NTSC:800x600 screen (oversized with autoscroll) with 8 colors (3 bitplanes deep):

	Screen=CUSTOM:00008004,800w,600h,3d,1

Notice that the first portion of the Screen specification is "CUSTOM:" If anything else shows up in the first 7 characters, then KingFisher assumes that you are actually specifying the name of a specific public screen, rather than a custom screen specification.

The next item, "00008004" is a hexadecimal representation of the screen mode ID from the Display Database. The following are standard values that you can use as a starting point.

	Mode ID		Resolution  (PAL)	Description
	--------	-----------------	----------------------
	00008000	 640 × 200  (256)	Hires
	00008004	 640 × 400  (512)	Hires-Interlace
	00008020	1280 × 200  (256)	SuperHires
	00008024	1280 × 400  (512)	SuperHires-Interlace
	- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
	00039020	 640 × 480		Productivity
	00039024	 640 × 960		Productivity-Interlace
	- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
	00041000	1008 × 800 (1024)	A2024-10Hz
	00049000	1008 × 800 (1024)	A2024-15Hz
	--------	-----------------	----------------------

The next three items, "800w", "600h", and "3d" are probably quite obvious to you: they are the width, height, and depth of the screen. The letters that follow the numbers are stored in the file only to more easily describe their purpose. The trailing "1" indicates that autoscrolling is enabled for the screen ("0" disables it.)

Here is an entry for an A2024 15Hz screen with 4 colors (2 bitplanes) and autoscroll disabled:

	Screen=CUSTOM:00049000,1008,800,2,0

Notice that in this example we left off the 'w', 'h', and 'd' letters. KingFisher doesn't care.
@endnode

@node PREFSDISPLAYPUBLIC "PREFERENCES/DISPLAY/Default public screen"
@prev PREFSDISPLAYCUSTOM
If you select this item when KingFisher is operating on a custom screen, it will close its window and screen, and reopen the window on the system's default public screen.

If you select this item when KingFisher is already operating on a public screen, it will close and reopen its window on the default public screen @{b}provided that the current public screen is not already the default.@{ub}
@endnode

@node PREFSDISPLAYCENTER "PREFERENCES/DISPLAY/Center main window"
KingFisher usually remembers the most recently used position of its window. If you rather KingFisher opened its display always in the center of the screen, simply select this item.

Whenever you @{b}resize@{ub} the window, KingFisher will automatically recenter the window.

Whenever you @{b}move@{ub} the window, KingFisher will turn off the "Center main window" option to accomodate your wish to place the window in a specific position.
@endnode

@node PREFSDISPLAYFRAME "PREFERENCES/DISPLAY/Frame groups"
When this option is selected, KingFisher will place "recessed" frames around groups of related gadgets to more clearly denote their relationships to each other. This will cause a somewhat more "cluttered" display and may not be pleasing to everybody, which is why it has been made an option.
@endnode

@node PREFSDISPLAYEXTERNALGADIMAGES "PREFERENCES/DISPLAY/Use external gadget images"
@next PREFSDISPLAYSTICKY
This option is available only if you are running Kickstart V39 or later.

If enabled, KingFisher will attempt to load image files to replace any of the 28 major buttons of its interface. This feature relies on @{b}Datatypes@{ub} to recognize and load the image files, so you may store the pictures in any format that your system can support. This may include any and all of the following: IFF, PNG, PCX, TIFF, TARGA, JPEG, BMP, SunRaster, GIF etc.

The size and colors of the supplied images define the size and appearance of the buttons they replace. It is suggested that a uniform, fairly modest set of colors be used to avoid running out of color pens too quickly, especially if you are operating KingFisher on a public screen, such as the Workbench.

KingFisher will cheerfully load @{b}huge@{ub} images and create a completely dysfunctional interface. In the interest of power vs. reason, it was decided to give you the power to hang yourself, hoping that you can explore reasonable boundaries on your own and not feel fettered by artificial restrictions. To guide you in your quest: KingFisher's internal buttons do not exceed 31×31 pixels.

WARNING: With Kickstart 3.0 a @{" dangerous problem " link KS30EXTERNBUG} exists (and is still eluding me!) where this option can @{b}crash your Amiga@{ub}!! As of version 2.26, KingFisher will warn KS 3.0 users of this problem and offer to abort the command to load external images.


@{b}How to specify a replacement button image@{ub}

Each button image is stored in its own file. Both the unselected and the selected state of the button must be provided, as KingFisher expects both. For a cheesy (but effective) ASCII representation, click @{" here " link GADIMGEXAMPLE}. If you have the example images installed (these ship only with upgrade copies of KingFisher due to diskspace limitations), then you may also get a @{" real image " link gad.square.FlagO.image/main}. The height of the image file you specify should have an even number of lines, and the division between unselected and selected image should occur exactly halfway.

The name of the a button's image file is a composite of two variables:

1. @{u}The Display Aspect Ratio@{uu}@{lindent 16}
The approximate resolution of KingFisher's display screen determines the aspect ratio. The @{b}ASPECT-ID@{ub} is used as part of the filename. For example, the following table describes how KingFisher sees the display aspects:
RESOLUTION	@{b}ASPECT-ID@{ub}
 640 × 200		"flat"
 640 × 256		"flat"
 320 × 200		"square"
 640 × 480		"square"
 800 × 600		"square"
1024 × 768		"square"
 320 × 400		"tall"
 356 × 592		"tall"

N.B. If you @{B}always@{UB} want a certain type of image to be loaded, regardless of the current display aspect ratio, then you must add an item @{B}DISPLAY-ASPECT@{UB} to the .prefs file with a value 0 (flat), 1 (square), or 2 (tall).@{lindent 0}

2. @{u}The Button Name@{uu}@{lindent 16}
Each of the 28 buttons that KingFisher uses as part of its interface has a @{B}GADGET-ID@{UB} which becomes part of the filename:
Upper left corner:@{lindent 32}
JumpToFirst, JumpToLast@{lindent 16}
Flag gadgets:@{lindent 32}
FlagD, FlagX4, FlagX3, FlagX2, FlagX1, FlagH, FlagO, FlagM, Flag8, Flag7, Flag6, Flag5, Flag4, Flag3, Flag2, Flag1@{lindent 16}
Browse gadgets:@{lindent 32}
DiskPrev, DiskNext, VersPrev, VersNext, FishPrev, FishNext@{lindent 16}
Searching gadgets:@{lindent 32}
SearchReverse, SearchForward, ExprHistory, SearchResult@{lindent 0}


@{b}Constructing Filenames from these Variables@{ub}

Filenames are constructed from @{b}ASPECT-ID@{b} and @{b}GADGET-ID@{ub} as "gad@{b}.ASPECT-ID.GADGET-ID.@{ub}image"

Example: "gad.@{u}square@{uu}.@{u}ExprHistory@{uu}.image"
Example: "gad.@{u}flat@{uu}.@{u}FishNext@{uu}.image"

Notice that the image files do not have filename extensions that specify their filetype (such as .IFF, .PNG, .TIFF, .JPEG, or .GIF) because you are using an Amiga and not one of those other computers.

If, despite all your valiant efforts, KingFisher seems to ignore an image file you've created for a button, check the following:

1. Are you running Kickstart V39 (3.0) or later?
2. Can MultiView display the image?
3. Is the image small enough not to use up available Chip RAM?
4. Have you named the image file(s) correctly?
5. Have you been a good friend to everyone recently? ;-)
@endnode

@node GADIMGEXAMPLE "Crude ASCII example of external image layout"
@next PREFSDISPLAYEXTERNALGADIMAGES
@font courier.font 13
  UUUUU
  UUUUU     Unselected image portion
  UUUUU
  UUUUU _____
  SSSSS
  SSSSS
  SSSSS     Selected image portion
  SSSSS

Image width = Button Width
Image height = 2 × Button Height
@endnode

@node KS30EXTERNBUG "Kickstart 3.0 Bug With External Images"
@prev PREFSDISPLAYEXTERNALGADIMAGES
@next PREFSDISPLAYEXTERNALGADIMAGES
Some Kickstart 3.0 Amigas seem to have no problem; others crash immediately when this option is selected. A workaround was introduced with KingFisher 2.23 but not released to the public, and the problem was not officially documented until KingFisher 2.26 was made available.

@{b}You can help me@{ub} track down the nature of this problem: if you have an Amiga with Kickstart 3.0 send me information about the following aspects of your configuration (no matter if you crash or if you don't, but tell me what happens):
@{lindent 8}
*	@{lindent 16}Your datatypes.library; use the CLI command "version full Datatypes.library"@{lindent 8}
*	@{lindent 16}Use Multiview to view one or more of the gad.#?.image files that KingFisher would attempt to load (see below for more information on the file naming scheme) and select Multiview's "About" menu-command to note down the image type (PNG or IFF ILBM or GIF or whatever.)@{lindent 8}
*	@{lindent 16}Find that particular datatype in the SYS:Classes/Datatypes/ directory and perform a "version full" command on that file, too.@{lindent 8}
*	@{lindent 16}Also, I need the same version information for your picture.datatype: "version full picture.datatype"@{lindent 8}
*	@{lindent 16}If you have any system enhancements or hacks installed that in any way alter the standard display methods on your Amiga, I need information on those, too. Examples of these would be CyberGraphX, Picasso96, EGS, Merlin etc. graphics cards drivers, as well as IPrefs, Layers or other such improvments as would be found in your startup-sequence, user-startup and SYS:WBStartup/ drawer.@{lindent 0}

Thanks!
(And yes, if you @{b}don't@{ub} have Kickstart 3.0 (V39) you can safely ignore this problem)
@endnode

@node PREFSDISPLAYSTICKY "PREFERENCES/DISPLAY/Sticky result window"
@prev PREFSDISPLAYEXTERNALGADIMAGES
When this option is selected, and a Search Result Window is open (see @{" Stop on each match " link PREFSSEARCHSTOPONEACH}) then moving or resizing the @{B}main window@{UB} causes the Search Result window to be repositioned as well. In effect, the Search Result Window "sticks" to the right edge of the main window as much as possible.
@endnode

@node PREFSDISPLAYDBTITLE "PREFERENCES/DISPLAY/Show database title"
When this option is selected, the title of the current database is displayed above the main text display area of the main window. If you rarely work with multiple databases and you are running on a relatively small display screen, you may wish to leave this option disabled to preserve valuable screen space.
@endnode

@node PREFSDISPLAYREFRESH "PREFERENCES/DISPLAY/Smart refresh"
When this option is selected (Smart Refresh), KingFisher's windows will (whenever needed) be refresh by Intuition's own buffers. This can be significantly faster on screens with little depth, but on deep screens (such as a large 256 color Workbench) this not only slows down the refreshing but also requires Intuition to set aside enough memory for the refreshing operation to work, which can be quite a lot.

In Simple Refresh mode the display may not always be updated at once when portions of the window are "damaged" by obscuring windows, but Simple Refresh (i.e. Smart Refresh OFF) can significantly improve the display's performance and reduce the program's memory requirements. Experiment!
@endnode

@node PREFSPRINT "PREFERENCES/Printing"
This submenu allows you to define printing-related things:

	@{" Load custom print format " link PREFSPRINTLOAD}
	@{" Use default print format " link PREFSPRINTRESET}

	@{" One fish per page " link PREFSPRINTONEPERPAGE}
	@{" Avoid page breaks " link PREFSPRINTAVOIDBREAKS}
	@{" Add index info " link PREFSPRINTADDINFO}
@endnode

@node PREFSPRINTLOAD "PREFERENCES/PRINTING/Load custom print format"
Load a @{" Custom Format " link CUSTOMFORMAT} from a file and applies this to every fish (record) that is printed.

KingFisher remembers the print format in use for every database.

To create or edit a custom format, use the @{" Edit custom format file " link EDITFORMAT} command.

To revert to the built-in default format, use the @{" Use default display format " link PREFSDISPLAYRESET} command.

Using AmigaOS Notification, the file specifying the print format is immediately updated if the version on disk is changed. The display will not reflect this change; printed output will. The notification change will not take effect during printing.
@endnode

@node PREFSPRINTRESET "PREFERENCES/PRINTING/Use default print format"
This command reverts back to the builtin default print format.

The command is unavailable if the default print format is already in use.
@endnode

@node PREFSPRINTONEPERPAGE "PREFERENCES/PRINTING/One fish per page"
By enabling this command, each record (fish) is printed beginning at the top of a new page.

This command is unavailable while the printer is in use by KingFisher. You need to first @{" Release printer " link PRINTRELEASE} before you can change this setting.
@endnode

@node PREFSPRINTAVOIDBREAKS "PREFERENCES/PRINTING/Avoid page breaks"
@font courier.font 13
The effect of this command is, perhaps, most easily described at hand of a little diagram to compare the effect visually. The idea is to prevent descriptions from being broken up by page breaks, forcing a record which will not fit on the current page to begin at the top of the next page:


	 NO  Avoid page breaks		 YES Avoid page breaks
	 _____________________		 _____________________
	|Name: KingFisher     |		|Name: KingFisher     |
	|Vers: 2.0            |		|Vers: 2.0            |
	|Text: blah blah blah |		|Text: blah blah blah |
	|      blah blah blah |		|      blah blah blah |
	|      blah blah.     |		|      blah blah.     |
	|                     |		|                     |
	|Name: MonkeyCommand  |		|Name: MonkeyCommand  |
	|Vers: 1.0            |		|Vers: 1.0            |
	|Text: blah blah blah |		|Text: blah blah blah |
	|      blah.          |		|      blah.          |
	|                     |		|                     |
	|@{B}Name: MonkeyCommand  @{UB}|		|                     |
	|@{B}Vers: 2.0            @{UB}|		|                     |
	|@{B}Text: blah blah blah @{UB}|		|                     |
	|---------------------|		|---------------------|
	|@{B}      blah blah blah @{UB}|		|@{B}Name: MonkeyCommand  @{UB}|
	|@{B}      blah blah blah.@{UB}|		|@{B}Vers: 2.0            @{UB}|
	|                     |		|@{B}Text: blah blah blah @{UB}|
	|Name: B5-Images      |		|@{B}      blah blah blah @{UB}|
	|:::::::::::::::::::::|		|@{B}      blah blah blah.@{UB}|
					|                     |
					|Name: B5-Images      |
					|:::::::::::::::::::::|

This command is unavailable while the printer is in use by KingFisher. You need to first @{" Release printer " link PRINTRELEASE} before you can change this setting.
@endnode

@node PREFSPRINTADDINFO "PREFERENCES/PRINTING/Add index info"
Index information is added to the printout for each record in the following format:

	.INDEXINFO=|DISK=1|FISH=17|FLAGS=8001|

This format will become a standard for a future @{" Product-Info Specification " link PI} and will be recognized by KingFisher's "Add Fish..." command.

This command is unavailable while the printer is in use by KingFisher. You need to first @{" Release printer " link PRINTRELEASE} before you can change this setting.
@endnode

@node PREFSEXPORT "PREFERENCES/Export"
This submenu allows you to define exporting-related things:

	@{" Load custom export format " link PREFSEXPORTLOAD}
	@{" Use default export format " link PREFSEXPORTRESET}

	@{" Export filename " link PREFSEXPORTFILENAME}
	@{" Use importable raw format " link PREFSEXPORTMARKERS}
	@{" Add index info " link PREFSEXPORTADDINFO}
@endnode

@node PREFSEXPORTLOAD "PREFERENCES/EXPORTING/Load custom export format"
The internal default export format is merely one way of formatting the information in the database for export files. Different types of databases, in fact, may require different export formats.

Custom export formats are kept in files on disk, and KingFisher remembers the export format in use for every database.

To remove a custom export format and revert to the builtin default, select the @{" Use default export format " link PREFSEXPORTRESET} command.

To create or edit a custom format, use @{" Edit custom format file " link EDITFORMAT}.

Note that the @{" Use importable raw format " link PREFSEXPORTMARKERS} option, overrides the custom export format completely.

Using AmigaOS Notification, the file specifying the export format is immediately updated if the version on disk is changed. The display will not reflect this change; exported data will. The notification change will not take effect during an export operation.
@endnode

@node PREFSEXPORTRESET "PREFERENCES/EXPORTING/Use default export format"
This command reverts back to the builtin default print format.

The command is unavailable if the default print format is already in use.

Note that the use of the @{" Use importable raw format " link PREFSEXPORTMARKERS} option overrides the use of custom or default formats entirely.
@endnode

@node PREFSEXPORTFILENAME "PREFERENCES/EXPORTING/Export filename"
By default, the export filename, if you never specify a different name, is t:KF2.output. If you prefer a different filename, this command will let you do so, and KingFisher will remember the name from one session to the next until you change it again. An implicit @{" Close export file " link PREFSEXPORTCLOSE} will be issued for you.
@endnode

@node PREFSEXPORTMARKERS "PREFERENCES/EXPORTING/Use importable raw format"
Forces the output to be in a special, re-importable format. The file can be transmitted via electronic mail (although national characters may not be preserved by the email transmission!) and can be added to any KingFisher Release 2 database through the Edit menu's @{" Add fish from file " link APPENDFILE} command.

Notice that while this option is selected any custom export format is effectively disabled.
@endnode

@node PREFSEXPORTADDINFO "PREFERENCES/EXPORTING/Add index info"
Index information is added to the export file for each record in the following format:

	.INDEXINFO=|DISK=1|FISH=17|FLAGS=8001|

This format will become a standard for a future @{" Product-Info Specification " link PI} and will be recognized by KingFisher's "Add Fish..." command.
@endnode

@node PREFSSEARCH "PREFERENCES/Searching"
This submenu allows you to define searching-related things:

	@{" Stop on each match " link PREFSSEARCHSTOPONEACH}
	@{" Case sensitive " link PREFSSEARCHCASESENSITIVE}
	@{" Trim blanks " link PREFSSEARCHTRIMBLANKS}
	@{" Simple substrings " link PREFSSEARCHSIMPLESUBSTRINGS}
	@{" Use Search Masks " link PREFSSEARCHUSEMASK}

	@{" External command on failure " link PREFSSEARCHALERT0EXTERN}
	@{" External command on success " link PREFSSEARCHALERT1EXTERN}
	@{" Flash/beep screen when done " link PREFSSEARCHALERTFLASH}

From here, you may also learn more about @{" Search Expressions " link EXPRESSIONS}.
@endnode

@node PREFSSEARCHSTOPONEACH "PREFERENCES/SEARCHING/Stop on each match"
If checked, KingFisher performs an @{b}interactive@{ub} search, stopping on each fish (record) where the search succeeded. Continue the search the way you started it.

If not checked, KingFisher performs a @{b}collective@{ub} search, creating a @{" Search Set " link SEARCHSET} in the process. When the search is complete, you are presented with the @{b}Search Result Window@{ub} which lists all fish (records) where the search succeeded. If no such window opens, then no fish (records) were found at all.
@endnode

@node PREFSSEARCHCASESENSITIVE "PREFERENCES/SEARCHING/Case sensitive"
When checked, then upper and lower case letters are treated during a search as distinct symbols, so that "a" is not the same as "A".

When not checked, then upper and lower case variations are immaterial during a search.

If, for example, you are looking for references to Kickstart and your search string consists of "KS" (abbreviation for Kickstart) you might be looking explicitly for only the all upper case version, and have no desire to locate words like these, too: tic@{U}ks@{UU} or pac@{U}ks@{UU}.
@endnode

@node PREFSSEARCHTRIMBLANKS "PREFERENCES/SEARCHING/Trim blanks"
When checked, causes trailing blank spaces in a search expression to be removed from the end of strings, unless these strings are explicitly quoted.

Blank spaces in a string gadget are usually quite invisible but may have a profound effect on the success of your search. Consider:

@{jcenter}@{u}name$kingfisher    @{uu}
@{jleft}
The spaces after "kingfisher" would tend to go unnoticed. If you want the spaces to be considered, it is suggested that you quote the string with spaces, such as: @{u}name$"kingfisher    "@{uu}, rather than uncheck this option.
@endnode

@node PREFSSEARCHSIMPLESUBSTRINGS "PREFERENCES/SEARCHING/Simple Substrings"
When checked, KingFisher will recognize most of the old @{b}KingFisher 1.x@{ub} expression syntax, which is powerful enough for most purposes (and somewhat simpler) but does not support the specification of field names and the use of DOS Regular Expressionsą.

This option is named "simple substrings" because that is all that @{b}KingFisher 1@{ub} supported: a search for substrings in the entire record.

The QuickIndex will not be used when this option is in effect, and standard @{b}KingFisher Release 2@{ub} @{" Search Expressions " link EXPRESSIONS} cannot be used, either.

__________
ą	@{lindent 8}KingFisher 1.x supported DOS Regular Expressions, too, but this feature is not supported as part of the @{b}Simple Substrings@{ub} mode.
@endnode

@node PREFSSEARCHUSEMASK "PREFERENCES/SEARCHING/Use search masks"
When checked, this option causes searches to rapidly scan for records matching the @{b}Search Mask@{ub} as defined by the @{" Edit Search Masks " link EDITMASKS} command. This feature represents an additional layer of selection / elimination before the regular expression evaluation is performed.
@endnode

@node PREFSSEARCHALERT0EXTERN "External command on failure"
When a search completes and has located no records, and this option is checked, then an external command is executed through the shell (CLI) as specified by the SEARCH-DONE0-COMMAND option in the @{" KingFisher2.prefs " link TOOLTYPES} file. The "0" in the option key represents "none" or "failure".

Example: @{b}SEARCH-DONE0-COMMAND=say "bummer! kingfisher found nothing."@{ub}

See also @{" Flash/beep screen when done " link PREFSSEARCHALERTFLASH} for a less complex alert option.

Note: The human speech software used by the SAY command was discontinued by Commodore after Workbench 2.1 (V38) was released. If you have this software on older disks you may want to consider installing DEVS:narrator.device and LIBS:translator.library. Both work perfectly with later releases of the operating system, and the SAY command can be a lot of fun!
@endnode

@node PREFSSEARCHALERT1EXTERN "External command on success"
When a search completes and has located at least one record, and this option is checked, then an external command is executed through the shell (CLI) as specified by the SEARCH-DONE1-COMMAND option in the @{" KingFisher2.prefs " link TOOLTYPES} file. The "1" in the option key represents "one or more" or "success".

Example: @{b}SEARCH-DONE1-COMMAND=say "woopee, kingfisher found something!"@{ub}

See also @{" Flash/beep screen when done " link PREFSSEARCHALERTFLASH} for a less complex alert option.

Note: The human speech software used by the SAY command was discontinued by Commodore after Workbench 2.1 (V38) was released. If you have this software on older disks you may want to consider installing DEVS:narrator.device and LIBS:translator.library. Both work perfectly with later releases of the operating system, and the SAY command can be a lot of fun!
@endnode

@node PREFSSEARCHALERTFLASH "Flash/beep screen when done"
When a search completes (regardless of success or failure), and this option is checked, then KingFisher will "flash" all screens so that if you are busy working on something else, the "flash" will alert you that something wants your attention. To customize this feature further, use Workbench's Sound Preferences; you may set this to "flash" all screens and/or play a sound on your speakers.

NOTE: This command will @{b}not@{ub} be executed if the screen upon which KingFisher's window is open is the front-most screen!

This option is available in addition to the more flexible @{" External command on success " link PREFSSEARCHALERT1EXTERN} and @{" External command on failure " link PREFSSEARCHALERT0EXTERN} options which require a little work on your part to configure.
@endnode

@node PREFSSAVE "PREFERENCES/Save Settings"
@next MENU-PREFERENCES
Saves all settings to a file of your choosing, which is the same file from where KingFisher loaded its settings when it started. Specifying a file is done with KingFisher's SETTINGS @{" tooltype " link TOOLTYPES} at startup.

If no file is provided, KingFisher will save to the file @{b}KingFisher2.prefs@{ub} in the current directory.

If no specific file was provided during startup, then KingFisher attempts to load its settings form the following files, one after other until it succeeds or finally fails:

	KingFisher2.prefs				(in the current directory)
	ENV:KingFisher/KingFisher2.prefs
	S:KingFisher2.prefs

If it finds one of these files during startup, then it will save to this file when you @{b}Save Settings@{ub}.

You can save settings with this command to any file of your choosing but KingFisher will not be able to find and actually use the file unless you are saving it according to the above specifications.
@endnode

@node HELPUSINGKF "HELP/Using KingFisher"
@prev MENU-HELP
KingFisher helps you...

a) Search for records matching your specification, and
b) Store new records.

Searching for records requires understanding what it is you are searching for. This requires an understanding of the @{" Search Expressions " link EXPRESSIONS} through which you explain to KingFisher what you are (or are not) looking for.

@{b}Search Expressions@{ub} are entered into the Search Expression gadget (press 'x' -- where the cursor appears, that's the place to type a @{b}Search Expression@{ub}, and a search is initiated by pressing either the reverse or forward search buttons (the arrows with question mark super-imposed.) A search may either collect all possible matches and present you with a list from which you may select at will, or it interactively stops as soon as a match is found, requiring you to press the search button again when you are ready continue. The @{" choice is yours " link PREFSSEARCHSTOPONEACH}.

Each fish (record) may have a combination of @{" flags " link GAD_FLAGS} set to indicate it as deleted, owned, hidden, or marked for later retrieval. Eight (8) flags are available for your own use. Searching with the additional @{" Use Search Mask " link EDITMASKS} in use can drastically reduce the number of searchable records and concentrate the search on the more likely candidates.

@{b}VersionLinks@{ub} are a useful feature of KingFisher that link related records so that you can easily jump forward or backward to related records in the database to follow a program's development. This allows you to quickly locate the earliest or latest versions of a program. The information used by the @{" Version Browse Buttons " link GAD_VERSBROWSE} is constructed when you use the @{" Build Version Links " link REBUILDLINKS} command.

The center piece of the GUI is a scrolling panel of text containing the description of the current record. The layout for this description is controlled by a format that you may @{" redefine " link CUSTOMFORMAT} for your own purposes.


@{b}Things that may not be entirely obvious@{ub}

  *	@{lindent 8}You can run multiple copies of KingFisher. Each copy can access the same or a different database. Each may perform an independent search. Some may be used for browsing, some for printing, some to export data...@{lindent 0}

  *	@{lindent 8}KingFisher's window is fully resizable and can live on public and custom screens.@{lindent 0}

  *	@{lindent 8}You can @{" paint your own buttons " link PREFSDISPLAYEXTERNALGADIMAGES}@{lindent 0}

  *	@{lindent 8}An ARexx interface to the @{" server " link KFSERVER} is provided through @{" RexxFisher " link REXXFISHER}
@endnode

@node HELPSEARCHING "HELP/Searching"
In order to make the most of KingFisher's powerful @{b}Search Expressions@{ub} you must know their syntax: if you do not know your tools, how can you make effective use of them? Work through the @{" Search Expression Tutorial " link EXPRESSIONS} to learn how!


@{b}Overview of Searching@{ub}

1.	@{lindent 8}Enter a @{b}Search Expression@{ub} in to the @{" Search Expression Gadget " link GAD_EXPRESSION}, or select a previously used expression from a "history" list by pressing the @{" Expression History Button " link GAD_HISTORY}@{lindent 0}

2.	@{lindent 8}Press either of the two @{" Search Buttons " link GAD_SEARCH} to initiate a search in reverse or forward direction.@{lindent 0}


@{b}Advanced Searching@{ub}

1.	@{lindent 8}You may restrict your search to fish (records) in the database that match a certain pattern of @{" flags " link EDITMASKS}. No significant time is spent examining records that do not match a certain pattern.@{lindent 0}

2.	@{lindent 8}You may elect to perform an @{b}interactive@{ub} or @{b}collective@{ub} search, depending on the state of the @{" Stop on each match " link PREFSSEARCHSTOPONEACH} option in the PREFERENCES/Searching menu.@{lindent 0}

3.	@{lindent 8}@{" Other options " link PREFSSEARCH} are available to alter the behavior of a search.@{lindent 0}
@endnode

@node HELPPRINTING "HELP/Printing"
When you print with KingFisher, the printer device is kept open so that you may add further records to the printout without having another program intersperse its output.

During that time Other programs are unable to open the printer device, of course, meaning that they cannot print until you quit KingFisher or use the @{" Release printer " link PRINTRELEASE} command from the Project menu.

You can also specify a different print format through the @{" PREFERENCES/Printing " link PREFSPRINT} menu, as well as dictate how records are broken up over page boundaries.
@endnode

@node HELPEXPORTING "HELP/Exporting"
Exporting records with KingFisher can mean two similar, but distinct operations: you may write records to a file the same way you might wish to print them on paper, or you export them so that they may be read back into KingFisher. Which way the Export command is to be used depends on how you configure the {" Use importable raw format " link PREFSEXPORTMARKERS} command in the @{" PREFERENCES/Exporting " link PREFSEXPORT} menu.

The file to which you export can also be selected from that menu. Selecting a new file will automatically close the previously used file (if it was open.) The file to which KingFisher exports records is kept open much like the printer device is kept open between print operations. Use the @{" Close export file " link EXPORTCLOSE} command from the Project menu when you are finished with the file.
@endnode

@node HELPDATABASES "HELP/Databases"
@next MENU-HELP
If you wish to make an existing database available to KingFisher, you have two options:

1.	@{lindent 8}@{" Install database... " link INSTALLDATABASE} through KingFisher's menu command (see @{" PROJECT menu " link MENU-PROJECT}) which handles the installation of a database fully automatically, even adjusting filename references, if necessary, to included the proper disk volume labels!@{lindent 0}

2.	@{lindent 8}@{" Perform the step manually " link TROUBLE_NEWDB} -- this section also offers information on what changes may be needed to a .kfdb file to make it work when KingFisher itself fails to handle step (1) properly on its own, @{b}or when you need to create a new database.@{ub}@{lindent 0}
@endnode

@node MENU-RESULT "CAUGHT FISH"
@prev MAIN
This page unintentionally left blank. Please try the Index or Table of Contents.
@endnode

@node CLOSE "CAUGHT FISH/Close window"
This will merely close the Search Set window. It will not lose the current Search Set. To open the Search Set window again, click on the icon which contains an image of Fred Fish's "Fish" logo emulating the shark from "Jaws."
@endnode

@node APPLYMASK "CAUGHT FISH/Apply Mask"
@next MAIN
This command applies a new mask to all fish in the Search Result window. More flexibility will be offered to this function in the future.
@endnode

@node ADVANCEDUSE "4 Advanced use of KingFisher"
@prev WORKING
@next REXXFISHER
This chapter addresses the variously complex aspects of KingFisher. You should be familiar with the topics of the previous chapter, @{" Working with KingFisher " link WORKING} before delving into the more complex topics of this one.

	@{lindent 24}@{" Custom Formats " link CUSTOMFORMAT} for the display, printer, and export files@{lindent 0}

	@{lindent 24}@{" Reconfiguring the KFServer " link KFSERVERPREFSFORMAT} through its preferences file@{lindent 0}

	@{lindent 24}@{" Customizing .kfdb files " link KFDBFORMAT} for optimum performance@{lindent 0}

	@{lindent 24}@{" The KingFisher2.prefs file " link TOOLTYPES} for advanced customizations@{lindent 0}

	@{lindent 24}@{" RexxFisher " link REXXFISHER} as an alternate or additional interface to the server@{lindent 0}

	@{" The KingFisher Developer Kit " link DEVKIT} helps you create additional @{b}client@{ub} software for KingFisher!@{lindent 0}

	@{" Paint the Buttons " link PREFSDISPLAYEXTERNALGADIMAGES} to alter KingFisher's appearance

	@{" Limitations " link LIMITS} part of KingFisher's design
@endnode

@node REXXFISHER "5 RexxFisher"
@prev ADVANCEDUSE
@next DEVKIT
@{b}RexxFisher@{ub}
@{b}Copyright © 1992,1993,1994,1995,1996,1997 Udo Schuermann@{ub}
@{b}All rights reserved@{ub}

@{b}RexxFisher@{ub} is a @{b}client@{ub} application that attaches to and provides an ARexx interface to the @{" KFServer " link KFSERVER}.

If run with a specific @{b}portname@{ub} on the command line, another application can communicate with a particular RexxFisher client. If the portname already exists, then RexxFisher will fail. If not given a specific portname, RexxFisher will create one: @{i}REXXFISHER1 @{ui} followed by @{i}REXXFISHER2 @{ui} and @{i}REXXFISHER3 @{ui} etc.

Results of calls are returned in the standard @{ub}result@{ub} variable (use "say result" to display a value returned by RexxFisher) and errors are returned in the @{b}portname@{ub}.LASTERROR variable, where @{b}portname@{ub} does @{b}not include@{ub} the increment number (1, 2, 3, etc.) added when RexxFisher is invoked without a specific portname. I.e. If RexxFisher's port happens to be 'REXXFISHER4', then the error variable is REXXFISHER.LASTERROR, without the '4.'

All commands are understood also with an RF_ prefix (ex. RF_QUIT instead of QUIT), which may be used to avoid confusion with ARexx or other commands. These commands may be used in any mix of upper and lower case characters.


@{b}Commands ALWAYS usable@{ub}
(These require no previous @{" HELLO " link RFHELLO}, nor a connection to the server)

	@{" DISABLE " link RFDISABLE}
	@{" HELP " link RFHELP}
	@{" QUIT " link RFQUIT}
	@{" VERSION " link RFVERSION}
	@{" LOCK " link RFLOCKING}
	@{" UNLOCK " link RFLOCKING}



@{b}Commands to establish a connection to the server@{ub}
(Will start the server if it is not already running)

	@{" HELLO " link RFHELLO}


@{b}Commands available only after a successful use of HELLO:@{ub}

	@{" ADDFISH " link RFADDFISH}
	@{" BYE " link RFBYE}
	@{" FIND " link RFFIND}
	@{" GETFISH " link RFGETFISH}
	@{" LIST " link RFLIST}
	@{" OBTAIN " link RFOBTAIN}
	@{" SELECT " link RFSELECT}
	@{" SET " link RFSET}
	@{" STATUS " link RFSTATUS}
	@{" USE " link RFUSE}


@{b}Demonstration Script@{ub}

For your enlightenment, the @{" RexxDemo.kfrx " link RexxDemo.kfrx/main} script is supplied. Please note that this script assumes that both the KFServer and RexxFisher are running in the background. Enter "rx rexxdemo.kfrx" to run the demo script from the CLI.
@endnode

@node RFVERSION "ARexx: VERSION"
Usage:
	VERSION

Returns RexxFisher's version tag, without the $VER: portion, of course. This will ALWAYS use the standard Style Guide compliant format such as:

	RexxFisher 1.5 (8.5.94)

Example:
	VERSION
	say "Welcome to" result
@endnode

@node RFHELP "ARexx: HELP"
Usage:
	HELP

Returns a list of all acceptable commands as well as some sort of command template to help you figure out what sort of parameters you might be able to get away with.

Example:
	say "These commands are available to you:"
	HELP
	say result
@endnode

@node RFQUIT "ARexx: QUIT"
Usage:
	QUIT

Tells RexxFisher to shutdown. In a real environment, you might want to issue a command such as "DISABLE QUIT" to prevent the QUIT command from being recognized. This will also suppress the command from being listed by HELP.

Despite a disabled QUIT, RexxFisher will respond to a CTRL_C signal such as those sent by the c:BREAK command.

Example:
	QUIT
@endnode

@node RFDISABLE "ARexx: DISABLE"
Usage:
	DISABLE command

Disables a command so that RexxFisher will no longer be able to execute it. This prevents accidental shutdown of RexxFisher, for example by a "rogue script." Disabled commands will not be part of the HELP listing.

Example:
	DISABLE QUIT
@endnode

@node RFHELLO "ARexx: HELLO"
Usage:
	HELLO "arbitrary identification"

Needs no previous login and will establish a connection to the KFServer. If the KFServer is not running, RexxFisher will attempt to start it in the exact same way that KingFisher (the GadTools client) tries to start KFServer. The only problem is that RexxFisher cannot (yet) be told to look in a place OTHER than the default directory for the KFServer. Start RexxFisher in the same directory where KFServer is located and all will be fine.

	You should give a nice and descriptive name along with the HELLO, such as:

	HELLO "BLAZEFISHER ARexx Script"
					(my apologies, Dan! :^)

If you issue HELLO when already connected, then RexxFisher will issue an implicit @{" BYE " link RFBYE} command to the server to disconnect you. RexxFisher will also do this when it is made to shutdown (either with QUIT or through a c:BREAK signal.)

Example:
	HELLO "test script"
@endnode

@node RFBYE "ARexx: BYE"
Usage:
	BYE

Sign off from the KFServer. This terminates your access to the server. If you forget this, then RexxFisher keeps the connection active for the next script, which may be confusing. RexxFisher has no idea, of course, if your script has terminated or is just idling around for no particular reason.

Example:
	BYE
@endnode

@node RFLIST "ARexx: LIST"
Usage:
	LIST

This obtains a list of all available databases from the server. The format of this list is as follows:

	"Description@{B}\\1@{UB}database.kfdb@{B}\\n@{UB}
	 Description@{B}\\1@{UB}database.kfdb@{B}\\n@{UB}"

Which means that there are one or more lines of text each of which begins with a nice descriptive text for the database followed by a @{B}\\1@{UB} character (which is an ASCII 1, ^A symbol) and followed then by the .kfdb name which you would need to give to the server through the @{" USE " link RFUSE} function to make a selection.

Example:
	LIST
@endnode

@node RFUSE "ARexx: USE"
Usage:
	USE database

This selects a database by giving it the name of a .kfdb file. Please see @{" LIST " link RFLIST} above for more information.

Example:
	USE "Miniature.kfdb"
@endnode

@node RFFIND "ARexx: FIND"
Usage:
	FIND "expression"
	FIND AGAIN
	FIND OPTION @{B}@{I}x @{UI}@{UB}

This command initiates, continues, or configures a search operation:

	FIND "expression"
		@{lindent 16}Allows the use of the same @{" expression syntax " link EXPRESSIONS} as KingFisher. The expression is compiled and the function begins a search at once. If you receive an error, the result string is in the format "Error X in column Y" where the error value X is one of these:@{lindent 0}

		@{U}X@{UU}	@{U}Meaning@{UU}
		1	@{" Comparison Operator Expected " link ERROR_CMPEXPECTED} ($ = != < > >= <=)
		2	@{" Logical Operator Expected " link ERROR_OPEXPECTED} (AND, OR, XOR)
		3	@{" Invalid Comparison Operator " link ERROR_INVALIDCMP} (ex: <! >< ... are bogus)
		4	@{" Mismatched Parentheses " link ERROR_MISMATCH}
		5	@{" Field Identifier Expected " link ERROR_FLDEXPECTED} (must use "field op value")
		6	 Unsupported Feature -- obsolete
		7	@{" Internal Error " link ERROR_INTERNALERR}
		8	@{" Incomplete Expression " link ERROR_INCOMPLETE}

		Example:
			FIND "name$kingfisher|name$aquarium"

	FIND AGAIN
		@{lindent 16}Search onward with the previously used expression. You must have an expression compiled with a previous @{I}FIND "expression" @{UI}command, otherwise this will not work.@{lindent 0}

		Example:
			FIND AGAIN

	FIND OPTION @{B}@{I}x @{UI}@{UB}
		@{lindent 16}Alter the behavior of the next FIND command according to the option @{B}x@{UB}:@{lindent 0}

		FORWARD				Search forward
		BACKWARD				Search backward
		CASEIGNORE			Upper/lower case ignored
		CASEEXACT				Upper/lower case important
		TRIMBLANKS			Trim trailing blanks off search-strings
		NOTRIMBLANKS			Do not trim blanks
		SIMPLEEXPRESSION		Uses original KF1.40 expressions
		COMPLEXEXPRESSION	Uses new KF2.0 expressions
		SHOW					List current options

		Example:
			FIND OPTION FORWARD
			FIND OPTION CASEIGNORE
			FIND OPTION TRIMBLANKS
			FIND OPTION COMPLEXEXPRESSION
			FIND OPTION SHOW
			say result

NOTE:	There is no way to interrupt a search in progress. Depending on user-feedback, a future version of RexxFisher may accept a break signal to interrupt a search.
@endnode

@node RFGETFISH "ARexx: GETFISH"
Usage:
	GETFISH fishnum
	GETFISH fishnum width
	GETFISH fishnum width displayformat

Retrieve a specific fish by record number. The command has a second, optional parameter that determines if the resulting string is formatted or retrieved in raw form. A positive number for the 2nd parameter indicates the column width of the display that the text should fit. The resulting text, when formatted, will have an appearance much like that in KingFisher's ListView.

A 3rd parameter specifies a @{" display format " link CUSTOMFORMAT} other than the default.

Notice that a record number of 0 retrieves the most recently retrieved record. It is best not to rely on this functionality, especially after a search operation but may be useful in some cases:

Example:
	GETFISH 3693

		@{lindent 16}Retrieves record 3693 without special formatting.@{lindent 0}

	GETFISH 3693 75

		@{lindent 16}Retrieves record 3693 without special formatting, but wordwraps the buffer to fit within 75 columns of non-proportional text.@{lindent 0}

	GETFISH 0 75 "NAME=\@{name}\\nAUTHOR=\@{author}\\nDESCRIPTION=\@{description}"

		@{lindent 16}Retrieves the last used record (0 has that special meaning), wordwraps the buffer to fit within 75 columns of non-proportional text, and uses a special custom format (the strange mess in ""'s) to determine what is included and how it is formatted.@{lindent 0}
@endnode

@node RFADDFISH "ARexx: ADDFISH"
Usage:
	ADDFISH "filename"

Adds all fish from the indicated file to the current database.

Example:
	ADDFISH 't:new-fish.txt'
@endnode

@node RFOBTAIN "ARexx: OBTAIN"
Usage:
	OBTAIN what

Obtains a variety of information from the server, according to the parameter given:

	DISK	@{lindent 16}The current disk number.@{lindent 0}

	FISH	@{lindent 16}The current fish number, usable as the 1st parameter to the @{" GETFISH " link RFGETFISH} command.@{lindent 0}

	FLAGS	@{lindent 16}The flag bits of the current fish; the values currently defined, although not necessarily setup for each fish, are:@{lindent 0}

		0x0100	Marked for retrieval
		0x0200	Marked for ownership
		0x0400	Marked to stay hidden in searches
		0x8000	Marked to be deleted

		@{lindent 16}Bits in the range 0x0001 through 0x0080 are user defined.@{lindent 0}

	PVER	@{lindent 16}The fish number of the PREVIOUS VERSION; the value 0 is returned if no previous version exists.@{lindent 0}

	NVER	@{lindent 16}The fish number of the NEXT VERSION; the value 0 is returned if no next version exists.@{lindent 0}

	DBNAME	@{lindent 16}The descriptive name of the database in use.@{lindent 0}

	DBFILE	@{lindent 16}The filename (ending with .kfdb) of the database in use. Such a filename can be passed to the @{" USE " link RFUSE} command.@{lindent 0}

	DBSIZE	@{lindent 16}The number of records in the current database, which is also the highest fish number you can pass to the @{" GETFISH " link RFGETFISH} command.@{lindent 0}

Example:
	OBTAIN DISK
	OBTAIN FISH
	OBTAIN FLAGS
	OBTAIN PVER
	OBTAIN NVER
	OBTAIN DBNAME
	OBTAIN DBFILE
	OBTAIN DBSIZE
@endnode

@node RFSELECT "ARexx: SELECT"
Usage:
	SELECT fishnumber

Selects a specific database record, but does not actually retrieve information. This is faster if all you need is use the OBTAIN command next, perhaps to locate a record with specific flags, or to follow a list of records along the VersionLinks.
@endnode

@node RFSET "ARexx: SET"
Usage:
	SET PVER fishnumber
	SET NVER fishnumber
	SET FLAGS flags

NOTE:	In prior versions this command was SETVLINK.

Sets the previous or next version link for the current fish. A value of 0 for the fishnumber indicates no previous or next version. It is up to you to assure that records are properly linked in both directions, as the KFServer will not interfere with your selections. Furthermore, if a record already has a link number set, this value will be replaced with the new selection.

Example:
	/* link record 17 to 76 and vice versa */
	SELECT 17
	SET NVER 76

	SELECT 76
	SET PVER 17

NOTICE: In older versions of this example, we used GETFISH instead of @{" SELECT " link RFSELECT} for improved speed.
NOTICE: Links need not be sequential. Thus, record 17 may have record 76 as its predecessor. Versions of KingFisher before 2.9 do not properly handle such cases, however.
@endnode

@node RFSTATUS "ARexx: STATUS"
Usage:
	STATUS

Retrieves status information from the server. This is effectively the same as what KingFisher displays in the Status command (rightAmiga-I) except that it applies to RexxFisher.

Example:
	STATUS
	say result
@endnode

@node RFLOCKING "ARexx: LOCK and UNLOCK"
Usage:
	LOCK
	UNLOCK key

Locking RexxFisher may be necessary to prevent other programs for inadvertently connecting to it and fouling up the current status while your ARexx script is passing information to another program, thereby having relinquished access to RexxFisher (i.e. ADDRESS REXXFISHER1; ... ; ADDRESS VLT ; ...)

LOCK returns (in the Rexx RESULT variable) a unique value which you should store. Pass this value to the UNLOCK command to unlock RexxFisher again. Without this key, RexxFisher will remain locked. ALWAYS call UNLOCK before exiting your script, else the key is (probably) lost and RexxFisher must be shutdown with a CTRL-C signal and restarted!

Example:
	OPTIONS RESULTS
	ADDRESS REXXFISHER1
	VERSION
	say RESULT
	LOCK
	myKey = RESULT
	ADDRESS VLT
	: : :
	ADDRESS REXXFISHER1
	UNLOCK myKey
	: : :
	BYE
	
@endnode

@node DEVKIT "6 Developing for KingFisher"
@prev REXXFISHER
@next SUPPORT
@{b}What is the KingFisher Developer Kit?@{ub}

If you have registered KingFisher you may get a KingFisher Developer Kit to help you create @{b}client@{ub} software for the KingFisher @{" server " link KFSERVER}:

  *	@{lindent 8}Instead of relying on ARexx and @{" RexxFisher " link REXXFISHER}, for example, you might wish to write a small, special-purpose @{b}client@{ub} to help your BBS users search for programs,@{lindent 0}

  *	@{lindent 8}You could write @{b}client@{ub} applications to perform extensive database manipulations,@{lindent 0}

  *	@{lindent 8}You might even want to write a replacement for the KingFisher GUI, perhaps using the MUI (Magic User Interface) system.@{lindent 0}

  *	@{lindent 8}Or maybe you're just curious what the interface looks like or what a little playing around could produce!@{lindent 0}

The KingFisher Developer Kit is available @{b}free@{ub} via email or (if you specify) as part of a regular upgradeą only from the @{" author " link AUTHOR}. The support API (Application Program Interface) you will receive in source form is written to compile with SAS/C 6.56 but it should also compile with DICE 3. It includes example source code to help you get started with a simple @{b}client@{ub} and build from there.


@{b}Features of the Developer Kit@{ub}

The following links will only work if you have the Developer Kit installed. The source code links work especially well if you have the C/C++ Datatype installed!

@{" kf-api.h " link "Developer/kf-api.h/main"}@{lindent 16}
All your @{b}client@{ub} programs @{b}#include @{ub}this file to obtain prototype declarations for functions, as well as various structures that are needed to interface with the @{" KFServer " link KFSERVER}@{lindent 0}

@{" kf-api.c " link "Developer/kf-api.c/main"}@{lindent 16}
You must compile this file (although a SAS/C 6.56 generated .o (object) file is also supplied for your convenience.) All your @{b}client@{ub} programs then @{b}link @{ub}with this .o (object) file. The file supports automatically starting the @{" KFServer " link KFSERVER}. All @{b}you@{ub} need to do is call the functions defined in the @{" kf-api.h " link "Developer/kf-api.h/main"} file.@{lindent 0}

@{" kf.h " link "Developer/kf.h/main"}@{lindent 16}
If you @{b}#include@{ub} @{" kf-api.h " link "Developer/kf-api.h/main"} then this file is automatically included, providing you with details on all @{" server " link KFSERVER} calls, such as expected parameters, return values, and details on error conditions.@{lindent 0}

@{" CLIent.c " link "Developer/CLIent.c/main"}@{lindent 16}
The very first @{b}client@{ub} program. I wrote this without the use of the "kf-api.(c|h)" files (they did not exist at the time) to effect early testing of the server even before the KingFisher GUI was written. Although this program compiles and works, it is also an example of @{b}how not to write a client@{ub} -- life is much easier with the use of the "kf-api.(c|h)" files!@{lindent 0}

@{" ReOrder.c " link "Developer/ReOrder.c/main"}@{lindent 16}
A good demonstration program to show how to use the functions in the "kf-api.(c|h)" files to your advantage. The program transfers one or more records from one KingFisher database to another, demonstrating how to access two databases simultaneously, how to select records, read from one and write to the other database.@{lindent 0}

@{" demo.c " link "Developer/demo.c/main"}@{lindent 16}
A small starter project to help you get stared. It merely provides a framework from which to expand.@{lindent 0}

@{" Status.IFF4 " link "Developer/Status.IFF4/main"}@{lindent 16}
A 4 bitplane (16 color) IFF ILBM (picture) that provides color-coded details on the output generated by a @{b}KFServer STATUS@{ub} command. This may prove helpful to developers to diagnose their software's behavior with respect to the @{" KFServer " link KFSERVER}.@{lindent 0}

@{" README " link "Developer/README/main"}@{lindent 16}
An introductory "ReadMe" file that describes how to get started with the Developer Kit.@{lindent 0}
__________
ą As diskspace is limited on floppy disks, @{" upgrades " link AUTHOR} that include the developer kit will not include the "1000 Fish Disk" database and vice versa.
@endnode

@node SUPPORT "7 Upgrades and Support"
@prev DEVKIT
@next TROUBLE
@{b}Upgrades@{ub}

You may obtain upgrades in any of the following ways:

  *	@{lindent 8}@{b}Free@{ub} by downloading new releases from @{" Aminet " link AMINET}, your local BBS, or new CD-ROMs,@{lindent 0}

  *	@{lindent 8}@{b}Free@{ub} by visiting the KingFisher World Wide Web home page at @{b}http://www.wam.umd.edu/~walrus/KingFisher.html@{ub}@{lindent 0}

  *	@{lindent 8}@{b}Free@{ub} keyfiles are are available to registered users via email. By regular mail ("snail mail") they require an @{" upgrade payment " link REGSITES} to cover distribution costs.@{lindent 0}

  *	@{lindent 8}By sending the appropriate payment to one of the @{" registration sites " link REGSITES}.@{lindent 0}


@{b}Technical Support@{ub}

If you do @{b}not have access to electronic mail@{ub}, please write to KingFisher's @{" author " link AUTHOR}. Except for two letters (which got lost a few years ago) I have always answered snail mail correspondence.

Technical support through email is available by email. Send a message to @{b}walrus@wam.umd.edu@{ub} detailing your questions, difficulties, suggestions, or requests. If you place the word "KingFisher" in the subject line, chances are that your message is answered more swiftly.
@endnode

@node KFSERVER "KingFisher Database Server"
KFServer is the @{b}server@{ub} portion of KingFisher's @{" Client-Server " link CLIENTSERVER} access model. The program is started automatically by the KingFisher (GUI) and RexxFisher (ARexx) @{b}clients@{ub}. KFServer requires that the file @{" KFServer.prefs " link KFSERVERPREFSFORMAT} is available and properly configured. @{b}KFServer@{ub} will not run if the file is missing or fails to specify required information.

Information on @{b}.kfdb@{ub} (Database Descriptor) files is available @{" here " link KFDBFORMAT}.
@endnode

@node KEYFILE "The Keyfile"
@prev MAIN
@next MAIN
@{b}@{i}"Not the dreaded keyfile!" @{ui}@{ub}

Making one set of patches available after another to keep all previous users of KingFisher up to date has not only become a chore for me but also a confusing and frustrating labor for others. In addition, the set of patches have grown to occupy nearly a megabyte of space on every site of the global @{" Aminet " link AMINET} and numerous local BBSs. Downloading a new set of patches requires quite a while each time a new version arrives, with perhaps as much as 90% of the downloaded portion useless to your particular version of KingFisher.

The solution to this increasingly painful dilemma is obviously a @{b}keyfile@{ub}. This is a file named @{b}.KingFisher.key@{ub} (notice the leading dot) whose content tells @{" KFServer " link KFSERVER} and @{b}KingFisher@{ub} that you have registered the program.

Starting with @{b}KingFisher 2.20@{ub}, only a single kind of executable will be distributed. The presence or lack of the @{b}keyfile@{ub} will determine registration status. You paid for your @{b}keyfile@{ub}. Keep it safe and don't let it fall into someone else's hands.

The @{b}keyfile@{ub} should be stored in the directory where @{b}KFServer@{ub} and @{b}KingFisher@{ub} are installed. If not found there, both programs will examine the environment variable KEYPATH (if it exists) and look in the directory specified there. If not found there, either, they will search for the file in the following logical volumes:

	KEYS:
	KEYFILE:
	KEYFILES:
	S:

If still not found, the software operates under the assumption that it is an unregistered copy.

@{b}Previously registered users are entitled to receive their keyfile via email for free. PGP is supported and recommended, but not required.@{ub}
@endnode

@node TOOLTYPES "Tooltypes & KingFisher2.prefs"
@prev MAIN
@next MAIN
KingFisher's preferences file is named @{b}KingFisher2.prefs@{ub}. A different filename can be specified with the use of the icon tooltype SETTINGS (example: "SETTINGS=KF2.prefs") This documentation assumes that the default name is in use.

The preferences file contains lines that can also be used in the icon tooltypes. KingFisher processes the preferences file before it processes the tooltypes, wherefore tooltypes (in icons) will override equivalent settings in the preferences file. This file is always re-created when KingFisher exits (with @{" Auto-save on exit " link PREFSAUTOSAVE} enabled) or when you specifically @{" Save Preferences " link SAVEPREFS}.

The following text describes @{b}only@{ub} settings that KingFisher will not allow you to alter from within the GUI.

Screen=@{lindent 16}
This setting describes the display screen on which KingFisher will open its windows. If blank, it will use the default public screen. If you are running Kickstart 38 or later, you need not concern yourself with this entry. Users of Kickstart 37 (2.04), however, should click @{" here " link CUSTOM37} for details on altering this entry.@{lindent 0}

Help-File=KingFisher2.guide@{lindent 16}
If you plan to store this .guide in a directory other than KingFisher's default directory, you should specify the full name here.@{lindent 0}

Search-Priority=-1
Search-Priority-Relative=Yes@{lindent 16}
Alters the priority of KingFisher while it is performing a search operation. If the 'Search-Priority-Relative' setting is set to 'Yes' then the given 'Search-Priority' is added to the current priority instead of representing an absolute value.@{lindent 0}

Search-Done@{b}1@{ub}-Command=
Search-Done@{b}0@{ub}-Command=@{lindent 16}
Notice the 1/0 that distinguishes these two entries. The 1 stands for "success"; the 0, for failure. That said, whenever a search completes, KingFisher will invoke one or the other shell command if they are defined. I use the following for myself:@{lindent 24}
Search-Done1-Command=SYS:Utilities/Say "KingFisher has found some fish!" >nil:
Search-Done0-Command=SYS:Utilities/Say "KingFisher found nothing." >nil:@{lindent 16}
To execute multiple commands, place them into a script file and invoke that.@{lindent 0}

End-Viewing-Command=@{lindent 16}
Whenever KingFisher is forced to leave View Mode (i.e. switch from viewing a Product-Info file back to viewing the database) then the command specified by this option is executed as a shell command. I use the following fr myself:@{lindent 24}
say "Oops, we are now back to viewing the database! >nil:"@{lindent 0}

MaxHistory=50@{lindent 16}
The maximum number of expressions kept in the expression history list. This value may not exceed 1024.@{lindent 0}

MaxHistHeight=10@{lindent 16}
The maximum height of the expression history window. This prevents the window from getting ridiculously tall when a lot of expressions are in the field. The window will be further limited by the amount of space beneath the expression history window and the bottom edge of the display screen.@{lindent 0}

MaxDBInfo=10@{lindent 16}
The maximum number of @{b}DBInfo@{ub} entries that KingFisher will maintain. This value may not exceed 1024. These entries store information on the position in previously visited databases, the display, print, and export formats in use, etc. Do not alter the @{b}DBInfo@{ub} lines by hand.@{lindent 0}

NoOutput@{lindent 16}
Suppresses the copyright banner that KingFisher ordinarily sends to the console when it first starts up.@{lindent 0}
@endnode

@node EXPRESSIONS "Search Expression Tutorial"
@prev MAIN
Search expressions provide a powerful mechanism for specifying what information you are looking for and what you are not looking for. To exploit KingFisher's true potential, it is necessary that you familiarize yourself with its expression syntax. This section helps you do that.

@{B}NOTE:@{lindent 16}	If you have the @{" Simple substrings " link PREFSSEARCHSIMPLESUBSTRINGS} option selected, then KingFisher will accept a simplified version of the expression syntax described here. Watch for the symbol @{fg fill}@{bg highlight} × @{bg back}@{fg text} to to point out important sections pertaining to this topic!@{UB}@{lindent 0}

To check the status of the "Simple Substrings" option, check the SEARCHING item in the PREFERENCES menu:

	|@{fg back}@{bg text} Preferences @{fg text}@{bg back}	   |
	| Global		» |
	| Display		» |
	| Printing		» |
	| Exporting		» |
	|@{fg back}@{bg text} Searching @{fg text}@{bg back}	   |________________
	|	|     Stop on each match			 |
	|	|     Case sensitive				 |
	|__ |     Trim blanks					 |
		|@{fg back}@{bg text}     Simple substrings @{fg text}@{bg back}			 |
		|     Use search masks			 |
		|___________________________|


For other options that affect searching, please see the @{" PREFERENCES/Searching " link PREFSSEARCH} menu.

	@{" Part 1:  A simple expression " link EXPR-1}

	@{" Part 2:  Composite expressions " link EXPR-2}

	@{" Part 3:  Sequence of evaluation " link EXPR-3}

	@{" Part 4:  Negation " link EXPR-4}

	@{" Part 5:  Expression shortcuts " link EXPR-5}

	@{" Part 6:  AmigaDOS patterns " link EXPR-6}
@endnode

@node EXPR-1 "Search Expression Tutorial, Part 1: A simple expression"
An @{I}expression @{UI} tells KingFisher exactly what you are looking for. An expression takes the form

	@{I}field @{UI}   @{I}comparison @{UI}   @{B}@{I}value @{UI}@{UB}

@{fg fill}@{bg highlight} × @{bg back}@{fg text}@{lindent 8}	When the Simple substrings option is selected, only the @{I}value @{UI}portion is used, and KingFisher automatically substitutes a @{B}*@{UB} (all) for the @{I}field, @{UI}and @{B}$@{UB} (substring search) for the comparison operator.@{lindent 0}

Choices for...

@{B}@{fg highlight}field@{fg text}@{UB}@{lindent 32}			the name of any @{" database field " link FIELDS} (see also the @{" Product-Info Specification " link PI}). An example of this would be name, description, version, or author. You may use a @{B}*@{UB} instead of a specific name to indicate that you wish KingFisher to search all existing fields in the records.@{lindent 0}

@{B}@{fg highlight}comparison@{fg text}@{UB}@{lindent 32}		one or two character symbol. The following are valid:@{lindent 0}
	=   or  ==@{lindent 32}	The field contents are equal to the value@{lindent 0}
	<>  or  !=@{lindent 32}	The field contents are not the same as the value@{lindent 0}
	<=	@{lindent 32}		The field contents are alphabetically less than or equal to the value@{lindent 0}
	>=	@{lindent 32}		The field contents are alphabetically greater than or equal to the value@{lindent 0}
	<	@{lindent 32}		... alphabetically less@{lindent 0}
	>	@{lindent 32}		... alphabetically greater@{lindent 0}
	$	@{lindent 32}		The field contents contain the substring given by the value@{lindent 0}
	#	@{lindent 32}		The field contents are compared to the given @{I}DOS Pattern.@{UI}@{lindent 0}

@{B}@{fg highlight}value@{fg text}@{UB}@{lindent 32}			a string of characters. If the string contains any of the special symbols, such as: ( ) & | ^ or blank spaces, it becomes necessary to enclose the string in single or double matching quotes: "" or ''@{lindent 0}

Examples:
	name=kingfisher
	version  >=2
	author  $  "matt dillon"

Notice that spaces surrounding the three parts of the expression (field, comparison, and value) are unimportant. In fact, spaces are not relevant in expressions and will be ignored unless they appear in a quoted string.

Next: @{" Composite expressions " link EXPR-2}
@endnode

@node EXPR-2 "Search Expression Tutorial, Part 2: Composite expressions"
Let us now combine two expressions to form a more complex one:

@{jcenter}name = kingfisher   &   version >= 2
@{jleft}
Notice the new symbol, @{B}&@{UB}, that we used. This is a boolean operator that you can use to connect two expressions. The following boolean operators are valid:

	@{B}@{fg highlight}&@{fg text}@{UB}	Logical AND

Both the expression on the left and on the right side of the operator must evaluate to TRUE, or else the combined expression formed from the two will evaluate to FALSE.

	@{B}@{fg highlight}|@{fg text}@{UB}	Logical OR
		Inclusive OR

If either or both of the expressions on the left and on the right side of the operator evaluate to TRUE, then the combined expression also evaluates to TRUE.

	@{B}@{fg highlight}^@{fg text}@{UB}	Logical XOR
		Exclusive OR

Either one, but NOT both expressions on the left and on the right side of the operator must evaluate to TRUE, otherwise the combined expression is FALSE.

The expression above, therefore, means: if the name equals 'kingfisher' AND the version is (alphabetically) greater than or equal to '2', then we have found a record that might be interesting.


Test your new-found understanding: What does the following mean? Refer to the @{" previous section " link EXPR-1} if you are not sure about the '$' symbol (I assume you are well versed with '=', no?)

@{jcenter}name $ 'aquarium'  |  name = kingfisher
@{jleft}
It means if the string 'aquarium' appears as a substring ($) in the name field, OR the name equals 'kingfisher' then this is a match.

Next: @{" Sequence of Evaluation " link EXPR-3}
@endnode

@node EXPR-3 "Search Expression Tutorial, Part 3: Sequence of Evaluation"
Let us examine a more complex expression. Assume we want to find all the records with 'aquarium' part of the name, OR all the ones named kingfisher which have a version of at least 2. Does the following expression work?

@{jcenter}name$aquarium   |   name=kingfisher   &   version>=2
@{jleft}
@{B}The answer is no!@{UB} KingFisher uses left-to-right evaluationą, meaning that the expression first evaluates

@{jcenter}name$aquarium
@{jleft}
then it evaluates

@{jcenter}name=kingfisher
@{jleft}
and then checks if EITHER is true. @{B}Only then@{UB} will it proceed to test the version. If we use parentheses to demonstrate how KingFisher actually evaluates the expression, we notice immediately that we had something else in mind:

@{jcenter}@{B}(@{UB} name$aquarium | name=kingfisher @{B})@{UB} & version>=2
@{jleft}
But KingFisher does understand parentheses, so we can easily fix the expression to do what we meant it to do in the first place. We just have to remember to use them:

@{jcenter}name$aquarium | @{B}(@{UB} name=kingfisher & version>=2 @{B})@{UB}
@{jleft}
@{B}@{fg highlight}You can use many levels of nested parentheses, and it is always safer to "overdose" on parentheses than to assume that the expression really means what you hope to express.@{fg text}@{UB}

Next: @{" Negation " link EXPR-4}
__________
ą@{lindent 8}	Many programming languages assign priorities to certain operations. Much like multiplication has priority over addition, the logical AND is often given priority over the logical OR. KingFisher, however, is strictly left-to-right in its evaluation.@{lindent 0}
@endnode

@node EXPR-4 "Search Expression Tutorial, Part 4: Negation"
Any part of the expression can be negated. If you wish to find all software in which Udo Schuermann had no part, you would begin by entering the following:

@{jcenter}name$"udo schuermann"
@{jleft}
and then @{I}negating @{UI}the expression by placing the negation operator in front of it:

@{jcenter}@{B}~@{UB}name$"udo schuermann"
@{jleft}
KingFisher recognizes both the ~ and the ! symbols as negation operators. Which one you use depends entirely on your preference.

Next: @{" Expression Shortcuts " link EXPR-5}
@endnode

@node EXPR-5 "Search Expression Tutorial, Part 5: Expression Shortcuts"
To make a variety of comparisons to a single field a little easier, an expression shortcut represents enhanced ease of entry and formulation; it does not affect the speed of searches in any way. Expression shortcuts are not available when the @{" Simple Substring " link PREFSSEARCHSIMPLESUBSTRINGS} is active.

Let us assume that you are looking for a large number of programs by name. You could enter the following expression:

@{jcenter}name$post | name$music | name$fish | name$king | name$aqua
@{jleft}
You will quickly come to the point where typing "name$" over and over becomes rather tedious. KingFisher allows you to enter the same expression this way:

@{jcenter}name$(post|music|fish|king|aqua)
@{jleft}
Observe that the expression in parentheses consists only of values and boolean operators (the | symbol in our example, signifying an OR-expression.) The field identifier ('name' in our example) and how this field is treated (as a substring, see the $ symbol) is a constant and does not change for the values given.

Consider:

@{jcenter}name="kingfisher" | name$"post"
@{jleft}
This expression cannot be converted to a shortcut because in one portion we test for equality (=) and in the other we test for a substring ($).

In order to impose an evaluation order, the portion in ()'s may contain multiple levels of parentheses to prioritize the evaluation order:

@{jcenter}name$(fish&@{B}(@{UB}king|net|sticks@{B})@{UB})
@{jleft}
represents:

@{jcenter}name$fish & @{B}(@{UB} name$king | name$net | name$sticks @{B})@{UB}
@{jleft}
Next: @{" AmigaDOS Patterns " link EXPR-6}
@endnode

@node EXPR-6 "Search Expression Tutorial, Part 6: AmigaDOS Patterns"
@next MAIN
The special comparison symbol '#' serves to identify the following string as a DOS Pattern. In case you are not familiar with these, look in your AmigaDOS manual (the AmigaDOS 3.1 manual describes these in Chapter 3, pp. 16-18) under the heading Pattern Matching and/or Wildcards.

Consider:

@{jcenter}name#"#?king#?"
@{jleft}
This pattern is the exact same thing as

@{jcenter}name$"king"
@{jleft}
except that the former uses the dos.library's pattern matching, whereas the latter uses a simpler, but faster substring comparison. Note especially the difference between the '#' vs. the '$' operator to tell KingFisher how you want the string treated.

The example above is probably as unexciting as a slice of stale bread, but if you are familiar with DOS Patterns, you should have already realized that they can help you build some powerful expressions. You must understand, however, that the dos.library matches the @{B}entire@{UB} expression against the field contents, whereby you will usually want to surround the string with the "0-or-more-characters" wildcard: #?
	The expression @{i}name#"king" @{ui}will NOT find "kingfisher", nor will it match any program that is not exactly named "king". Read the DOS documentation for more details. Enough said.

NOTE:	The @{" Trim Blanks " link PREFSSEARCHTRIMBLANKS} option will affect the search string, unless it is enclosed in quotes. @{B}@{U}You are strongly urged to always enclose your DOS Patterns in quotes!@{UU}@{UB}

NOTE:	If you specify a DOS Pattern that contains no wildcards, in other words it is a simple string constant, then KingFisher will convert the expression to an equality search. Example:

@{jcenter}name # "kingfisher"
@{jleft}
will not use the dos.library for pattern matching, but rather convert the expression to

@{jcenter}name = "kingfisher"
@{jleft}
and evaluate the equality directly and without assistance from DOS.


@{B}And that concludes our tutorial on expressions.@{UB}
@endnode

@node CLIENTSERVER "Client-Server Technology"
@prev MAIN
@next MAIN
@{b}What is "Client-Server"?@{ub}

Client-Server is a database technology whereby one unique portion of the software, called the @{b}server@{ub}, is responsible for controlling access to data, while one or more @{b}clients@{ub} talk to this server and request data. It is the @{b}clients@{ub} that are responsible for presenting the data, perhaps alter it and then handing it back to the server for storage; It is the server's responsibility to make sure that @{b}clients@{ub} don't update the same data simultaneously.

The Client-Server model provides for efficient, successful, and safe multiuser arbitration and is widely used in the computer industry.

KingFisher implements the powerful Client-Server concept to provide you with safe access to one or more databases, and to extend this access, if you wish, to a number of simultaneous users that may have access to your system through BBS software.


@{b}How does KingFisher implement Client-Server Technology on the Amiga?@{ub}

The Amiga's multitasking Exec (the software that handles all aspects of multitasking, including interprocess communication) provides a highspeed method of passing large amounts of information from one task to another. Hundreds, if not thousands of messages can be exchanged by two tasks every second!

When the @{" KFServer " link KFSERVER} is started, it creates a @{ub}message port@{ub}, a type of @{i}rendezvous @{ui}point between programs, to which @{b}clients@{ub} deposit requests for processing. The server processes these requests one after anther (first come, first served; FIFO) and returns the results to the sending process.

And that, quite frankly, is all there is to it!

Naturally, the protocol of how exactly to ask the KFServer for information requires some attention to detail. If you are interested in writing @{b}client@{ub} software for KFServer and you are a registered user, you are eligible for the @{b}free@{ub} @{" KingFisher Developer Kit " link DEVKIT} to help you get started. This package takes care of all the gruesome details of exchanging messages between your application and the server.

References:
  *	@{lindent 8}AMIGA ROM Kernel Reference Manual: Libraries. Exec Chapter.@{lindent 0}
  *	@{lindent 8}COMMODORE-AMIGA "C" include files: exec/ports.h@{lindent 0}
@endnode

